How Trojan Horse works:

The Trojan Horse hijacks the video route message to include emulation mode
information to line card.

When in emulation mode, an input IP packet's destination UDP port will be
mapped to the default Palm Beach UDP port map.

For example, in 24-qam emulation mode, input UDP port 0x0203 will be
mapped to QAM 2, program 3.  According to the default Palm Beach UDP
port map, the corresponding UDP port number should be 0xd843
(assuming PB in slot 3).  Hence the packet's destination UDP port
will be changed to 0xd843.  Everything works as if in normal Palm Beach
mode after this point.


How to support cloning in Trojan Horse modes:

Using the above example, if we also want to map that UDP to QAM 4, program 5,
we can use the following CLI:

video 3 udp 0x0203 qam 3/2.2 program 5

Internally, CC needs to do similar mapping from the input UDP to the default
Palm Beach UDP (0x0203 -> 0xd843), and store this cloning port map in its data
structure.

When the input session 0x0203 actually starts, Palm Beach will detect it and
report it to IOS with session_start message, UDP port 0xd843.  CC should
then configure the mux module on the line card to set up QAM 2, program 3,
as well as QAM 4, program 5 to output this session.

